  <h2>Ontario Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Ontario spans multiple climate patterns — from the Great Lakes corridor to northern boreal regions.
    Frost timing, growing degree day accumulation, and effective season length can vary dramatically
    depending on how close you are to large bodies of water and how far north you garden.
  </p>

  <h3>1) The Great Lakes create longer seasons</h3>
  <p>
    Southern Ontario near Lakes Ontario, Erie, and Huron often benefits from moderated temperatures.
    Spring may warm slightly slower, but fall frost is frequently delayed compared to inland areas.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Longer fall windows</strong> improve odds for full-season tomatoes and peppers.</li>
    <li><strong>Lake-effect moderation</strong> reduces extreme temperature swings.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>2) Northern Ontario is a different climate</h3>
  <p>
    As you move north, frost-free windows shrink and total seasonal heat declines.
    Long daylight helps, but warm-season crops must be chosen carefully.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you're gardening in a tighter window, this guide on
    <a href="/guides/what-crops-grow-in-short-growing-seasons/">
      crops that grow well in short growing seasons
    </a>
    can help set realistic expectations.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Spring volatility is common</h3>
  <p>
    Late spring cold snaps are not unusual, especially away from the lakes.
    Planting strictly by a calendar date can expose transplants to setbacks.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you’ve ever wondered why your “average last frost” wasn’t accurate,
    <a href="/guides/why-your-last-frost-date-isnt-exact/">
      this explains why frost dates aren’t exact
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Late-season planning matters</h3>
  <p>
    In much of Ontario, new long-maturity warm crops planted after mid-summer
    become increasingly risky unless you're in the warmest southern zones.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    To evaluate whether a crop will realistically finish,
    <a href="/guides/will-my-crop-mature-before-first-frost/">
      here’s how to estimate maturity before first frost
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Identify whether you’re in a lake-moderated or inland region.</li>
    <li>Match crop maturity to remaining seasonal heat.</li>
    <li>Add margin if you garden inland, at elevation, or in a frost-prone low spot.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Ontario, location within the province often matters as much as the province itself.
  </p>
</section>